 the State Flag of the Russian Federation\" (including amendments)]. pravo.gov.ru {{in lang|ru}} \n* [http://www.rbvex.it/russia.html Timeline Russian National Flag] {{in lang|it}}\n* [http://www.hrono.ru/heraldicum/flagi/home.htm Flag of Russia \u2013 old link] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://www.vexillographia.ru/russia/index.htm Flag of Russia \u2013 Vexillographia] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://33tura.ru/russia-flag Flag of Russia] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://flot.com/symbols/anflag.htm National Flag and Naval Ensign in Russia Navy] {{in lang|ru}}\n\n{{Russia topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Flag of|title=[[Flags of Asia]]}}\n{{Flag of Europe}}\n{{nationalflags}}\n{{Moscow Victory Parade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flag of Russia}}\n[[Category:Flags of Russia| ]]\n[[Category:National flags|Russia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Rustycaddy17", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up the introduction of the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_of_Russia"}
{"title_page": "Maricourt Catholic School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name         = Maricourt Catholic School\n| image        = Maricourt Catholic High School Crest.png\n| image_size   = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.508|-2.938|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto        = {{lang-la|Gaudeamus in Domino}}<br>\"Let us Rejoice in the Lord\"\n| established  = 1957\n| closed       = \n| type         = [[Voluntary Aided School|Voluntary Aided]]\n| religious_affiliation     = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| president    = \n| head_label   = \n| head         = \n| r_head_label = \n| r_head       = \n| chair_label  = \n| chair        = \n| founders      = [[Sisters of Mercy]]\n| address       = Hall Lane\n| city         = [[Maghull]]\n| county       = [[Merseyside]]\n| country      = [[United Kingdom]]\n| postcode     = [[L postcode area|L31 3DZ]]\n| local_authority          = [[Sefton Metropolitan Borough Council|Sefton]]\n| ofsted       = yes\n| urn          = 104960\n| staff        = \n| enrolment   = 1,300 \n| gender       = [[Coeducational|Mixed]]\n| lower_age    = 11\n| upper_age    = 18\n| houses       = \n| colours      = Maroon and Gold\n{{color box|Maroon}}{{color box|Gold}}{{color box|Maroon}}{{color box|Gold}}{{color box|Maroon}} \n| publication  = Maricourt Voice\n| free_label_1 = \n| free_1       = \n| free_label_2 = Diocese \n| free_2       = [[Archdiocese of Liverpool]]\n| free_label_3 = \n| free_3       = \n| website      = http://www.maricourt.net\n}}\n\n'''Maricourt Catholic School''', in [[Maghull]], [[Merseyside]], [[United Kingdom]], formerly ''Mater Misericordiae Grammar School'', was one of two [[Roman Catholic]] [[secondary school]]s administered by the [[Sisters of Mercy]] in [[Merseyside]], the other being [[Broughton Hall High School|Broughton Hall]], [[West Derby]]. The school celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2007 with the new headmaster Mr Brendan McLoughlin. The former headteacher Sister Mary Teresa RSM [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] was the last of the Sisters to be Head the school and ceased her duties in 2007, opting to remain as deputy chair of the Board of Governors. The school offered both [[GCSE]] and [[Advanced Level]] qualifications for male and female students. \n\n==History==\nThe school was founded by the Sisters of Mercy on 12 September 1957, originally known as ''Mater Misericordiae Grammar School''. It opened in the convent parlour of Quarry Brook House, former home of [[Meccano]] inventor and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Frank Hornby]], with only 16 eleven-year-old girls. The school eventually moved to the first small external section in January 1958. This section was formally blessed by Cardinal Heenan on 8 March in the same year. Due to the interest taken in it by the Bootle Education Committee, it rapidly grew in building size and pupil numbers, and became a voluntary aided [[Grammar School]] in September 1964, maintained by the Bootle Authority.\n\nThe school continued to run as a grammar school until November 1967, when the then [[Archbishop of Liverpool]], Dr Andrew Beck, approached the sisters to see if they would take over a nearby secondary school that had not yet opened,  St. Paul's Catholic Secondary Modern. They agreed, and in September 1968 it was annexed to their existing building. It was the first co-educational voluntary aided school in the Archdiocese, opened under the new title of ''Maricourt Catholic High School'', with Sister Mary Magdalen as headmistress. She retired at Christmas in 1989 and was succeeded by Sister Mary Teresa, who led the school until 2007. The school is now the largest Catholic secondary school in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Sefton]]. A jubilee mass was celebrated on 21 September 2007 in the [[Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral]]. The chief celebrant was the [[Archbishop of Liverpool]], Patrick Kelly, with thousands of friends, students, past and present attending the ceremony to celebrate the milestone.\n\n==Sixth Form==\nThe [[Sixth Form]] at Maricourt was rated as gaining some of the highest [[Advanced Level]] results in [[Merseyside]] and stand consistently above the national average,<ref>{{cite web|title=Department for Education KS5 Results|url=http://www.education.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/school_10.pl?No=3434621&Type=LA&Begin=c1&Num=343&Phase=2&Year=10&Base=c|work=National Results}}</ref> as well as enjoying a regular 100% pass rate for Advanced Level students. Maricourt works alongside [[Maghull High School]] and [[Deyes High School]] to form the ''Maghull Collaborative'', in which students may study across these sixth forms to broaden the A-Level curriculum available within them. Facilities at Maricourt, based in Quarry Brook House, were subject to substantial refurbishment during the 2011 August Holidays with modified study areas as well as the conversion of one of Quarry Brook's larger first floor rooms into an Oratory for use by students.\n\n== School Grounds ==\nMaricourt is split across two sites, Newman Hall and Arnold Hall, upper and lower school respectively. Newman Hall, named in the honour of [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[John Henry Newman]], is considered the school's main site and is home to both the administrative offices and most subject offices. School years 9 to 11 and the [[Sixth Form]] reside on this site for the majority of their lessons, and years 7 and 8 visit the site to use the available facilities, such as sports, drama and technology. Arnold Hall, previously the site of St Paul's Comprehensive, serves as the primary site for years 7 and 8, with sports facilities and rooms used by all students. Both sites have a large field used for recreation, physical education and sporting events. \n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Newman Maricourt Map.png|1000px|centre|Newman Hall]] -->\n\n==Mission and Ethos==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = '''''Maricourt seeks to  provide and sustain a living Roman Catholic community which is rooted in Christian values and where growth and knowledge, respect, love and friendship are shared by all.'''''\n| align = center\n}}\n\nThe mission statement is represented by a tree, symbolising Maricourt as a living community; with each year new people joining, whilst others move to the world of work or higher education. The school ethos fosters the development of each individual, a proper sense of self-worth, a sense of responsibility and respect for others. The school was founded in the tradition of the Sisters of Mercy, an institute founded for the service of those in need. Today, this is reflected in the school's intensive charity, such as the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Liverpool#Nugent Care Society|Good Shepherd Appeal]] and other local organisations.\n\n== Previous Headteachers ==\nSince its opening in 1957, the school has had four headteachers. Until 2007 previous headteachers had been both female and members of the Sisters of Mercy.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Active \n|-\n| Sister Mary Magdalen RSM || 1957\u20131989\n|-\n| Sister Mary Teresa RSM [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] || 1989\u20132007\n|-\n| Mr Charlie Adam [[Master of Arts|MA]]  || 2007 \u2013 2019\n|-\n| [[Mark Henry|Mr Mark Henry]]  || 2019 - Present\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable former pupils==\nAlumni of Maricourt Catholic High School are known as '''Old Maricourtians'''. Noted Old Maricourtians include:<ref name=Maricourt>{{cite web |title=At Maricourt our pupils have represented the following international teams... |url=http://www.maricourt.net/uploads/vlecontent/home/17/docs/Internationals.pdf |publisher=Maricourt Catholic School |format=PDF |page=8 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Heidi Range]], member of British girlband [[Sugababes]].\n*[[Kent Riley]], actor who starred in the British soap [[Hollyoaks]].\n*[[Simon Richman]], professional footballer.\n*[[Stephen Darby]], professional footballer.\n*[[Aaron McGowan]], professional footballer.\n*[[Joe Rafferty]], professional footballer.\n*[[Liam Nolan (footballer)|Liam Nolan]], professional footballer.\n*[[Jimmy Ryan (footballer, born 1988)|Jimmy Ryan]], professional footballer.\n*[[Dominic McGiveron]], professional footballer.\n*[[Alex Whittle]], professional footballer.\n*[[Adam Cummins]], professional footballer.\n*[[Paul Lewis (footballer)|Paul Lewis]], professional footballer.\n*[[Conor Grant]], professional footballer.\n*[[George Green (footballer, born 1996)|George Green]], professional footballer.\n*[[Niall Watson]], professional footballer.\n*[[Tom Scully]], professional footballer.\n*[[Terry McPhillips]], former professional footballer.<ref>[http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/junior-football/2009/12/22/tms-s-dedication-to-youth-football-earns-prestigious-fa-award-100252-25444343/ Liverpool echo]</ref>\n*[[Harvey Price ]], [[show jumping|Show jumper]] and [[2012 London Olympics|Olympic]] gold medalist.\n*[[Ninja (video game player)|Ninja]], professional fortnite expert.\n*[[Rick Astley]], global treasure, he will never give you up or let you down!\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sefton.gov.uk/ Sefton Metropolitan Borough Council official site]\n*[http://www.mass.freeuk.com// Associates of the Sisters of Mercy official site]\n*[http://www.mercyworld.org/ Website of the Sisters of Mercy]\n\n{{Schools in Sefton}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in the Archdiocese of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1957]]\n[[Category:1957 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Sisters of Mercy schools]]\n[[Category:Voluntary aided schools in England]]\n[[Category:Maghull]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name         = Maricourt Catholic School\n| image        = Maricourt Catholic High School Crest.png\n| image_size   = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.508|-2.938|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto        = {{lang-la|Gaudeamus in Domino}}<br>\"Let us Rejoice in the Lord\"\n| established  = 1957\n| closed       = \n| type         = [[Voluntary Aided School|Voluntary Aided]]\n| religious_affiliation     = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| president    = \n| head_label   = \n| head         = \n| r_head_label = \n| r_head       = \n| chair_label  = \n| chair        = \n| founders      = [[Sisters of Mercy]]\n| address       = Hall Lane\n| city         = [[Maghull]]\n| county       = [[Merseyside]]\n| country      = [[United Kingdom]]\n| postcode     = [[L postcode area|L31 3DZ]]\n| local_authority          = [[Sefton Metropolitan Borough Council|Sefton]]\n| ofsted       = yes\n| urn          = 104960\n| staff        = \n| enrolment   = 1,300 \n| gender       = [[Coeducational|Mixed]]\n| lower_age    = 11\n| upper_age    = 18\n| houses       = \n| colours      = Maroon and Gold\n{{color box|Maroon}}{{color box|Gold}}{{color box|Maroon}}{{color box|Gold}}{{color box|Maroon}} \n| publication  = Maricourt Voice\n| free_label_1 = \n| free_1       = \n| free_label_2 = Diocese \n| free_2       = [[Archdiocese of Liverpool]]\n| free_label_3 = \n| free_3       = \n| website      = http://www.maricourt.net\n}}\n\n'''Maricourt Catholic School''', in [[Maghull]], [[Merseyside]], [[United Kingdom]], formerly ''Mater Misericordiae Grammar School'', was one of two [[Roman Catholic]] [[secondary school]]s administered by the [[Sisters of Mercy]] in [[Merseyside]], the other being [[Broughton Hall High School|Broughton Hall]], [[West Derby]]. The school celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2007 with the new headmaster Mr Brendan McLoughlin. The former headteacher Sister Mary Teresa RSM [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] was the last of the Sisters to be Head the school and ceased her duties in 2007, opting to remain as deputy chair of the Board of Governors. The school offered both [[GCSE]] and [[Advanced Level]] qualifications for male and female students. \n\n==History==\nThe school was founded by the Sisters of Mercy on 12 September 1957, originally known as ''Mater Misericordiae Grammar School''. It opened in the convent parlour of Quarry Brook House, former home of [[Meccano]] inventor and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Frank Hornby]], with only 16 eleven-year-old girls. The school eventually moved to the first small external section in January 1958. This section was formally blessed by Cardinal Heenan on 8 March in the same year. Due to the interest taken in it by the Bootle Education Committee, it rapidly grew in building size and pupil numbers, and became a voluntary aided [[Grammar School]] in September 1964, maintained by the Bootle Authority.\n\nThe school continued to run as a grammar school until November 1967, when the then [[Archbishop of Liverpool]], Dr Andrew Beck, approached the sisters to see if they would take over a nearby secondary school that had not yet opened,  St. Paul's Catholic Secondary Modern. They agreed, and in September 1968 it was annexed to their existing building. It was the first co-educational voluntary aided school in the Archdiocese, opened under the new title of ''Maricourt Catholic High School'', with Sister Mary Magdalen as headmistress. She retired at Christmas in 1989 and was succeeded by Sister Mary Teresa, who led the school until 2007. The school is now the largest Catholic secondary school in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Sefton]]. A jubilee mass was celebrated on 21 September 2007 in the [[Liverpool Metropolitan Cathedral]]. The chief celebrant was the [[Archbishop of Liverpool]], Patrick Kelly, with thousands of friends, students, past and present attending the ceremony to celebrate the milestone.\n\n==Sixth Form==\nThe [[Sixth Form]] at Maricourt was rated as gaining some of the highest [[Advanced Level]] results in [[Merseyside]] and stand consistently above the national average,<ref>{{cite web|title=Department for Education KS5 Results|url=http://www.education.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/school_10.pl?No=3434621&Type=LA&Begin=c1&Num=343&Phase=2&Year=10&Base=c|work=National Results}}</ref> as well as enjoying a regular 100% pass rate for Advanced Level students. Maricourt works alongside [[Maghull High School]] and [[Deyes High School]] to form the ''Maghull Collaborative'', in which students may study across these sixth forms to broaden the A-Level curriculum available within them. Facilities at Maricourt, based in Quarry Brook House, were subject to substantial refurbishment during the 2011 August Holidays with modified study areas as well as the conversion of one of Quarry Brook's larger first floor rooms into an Oratory for use by students.\n\n== School Grounds ==\nMaricourt is split across two sites, Newman Hall and Arnold Hall, upper and lower school respectively. Newman Hall, named in the honour of [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[John Henry Newman]], is considered the school's main site and is home to both the administrative offices and most subject offices. School years 9 to 11 and the [[Sixth Form]] reside on this site for the majority of their lessons, and years 7 and 8 visit the site to use the available facilities, such as sports, drama and technology. Arnold Hall, previously the site of St Paul's Comprehensive, serves as the primary site for years 7 and 8, with sports facilities and rooms used by all students. Both sites have a large field used for recreation, physical education and sporting events. \n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Newman Maricourt Map.png|1000px|centre|Newman Hall]] -->\n\n==Mission and Ethos==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = '''''Maricourt seeks to  provide and sustain a living Roman Catholic community which is rooted in Christian values and where growth and knowledge, respect, love and friendship are shared by all.'''''\n| align = center\n}}\n\nThe mission statement is represented by a tree, symbolising Maricourt as a living community; with each year new people joining, whilst others move to the world of work or higher education. The school ethos fosters the development of each individual, a proper sense of self-worth, a sense of responsibility and respect for others. The school was founded in the tradition of the Sisters of Mercy, an institute founded for the service of those in need. Today, this is reflected in the school's intensive charity, such as the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Liverpool#Nugent Care Society|Good Shepherd Appeal]] and other local organisations.\n\n== Previous Headteachers ==\nSince its opening in 1957, the school has had four headteachers. Until 2007 previous headteachers had been both female and members of the Sisters of Mercy.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Active \n|-\n| Sister Mary Magdalen RSM || 1957\u20131989\n|-\n| Sister Mary Teresa RSM [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] || 1989\u20132007\n|-\n| Mr Charlie Adam [[Master of Arts|MA]]  || 2007 \u2013 2019\n|-\n| [[Mark Henry|Mr Mark Henry]]  || 2019 - Present\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable former pupils==\nAlumni of Maricourt Catholic High School are known as '''Old Maricourtians'''. Noted Old Maricourtians include:<ref name=Maricourt>{{cite web |title=At Maricourt our pupils have represented the following international teams... |url=http://www.maricourt.net/uploads/vlecontent/home/17/docs/Internationals.pdf |publisher=Maricourt Catholic School |format=PDF |page=8 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Heidi Range]], member of British girlband [[Sugababes]].\n*[[Kent Riley]], actor who starred in the British soap [[Hollyoaks]].\n*[[Simon Richman]], professional footballer.\n*[[Stephen Darby]], professional footballer.\n*[[Aaron McGowan]], professional footballer.\n*[[Joe Rafferty]], professional footballer.\n*[[Liam Nolan (footballer)|Liam Nolan]], professional footballer.\n*[[Jimmy Ryan (footballer, born 1988)|Jimmy Ryan]], professional footballer.\n*[[Dominic McGiveron]], professional footballer.\n*[[Alex Whittle]], professional footballer.\n*[[Adam Cummins]], professional footballer.\n*[[Paul Lewis (footballer)|Paul Lewis]], professional footballer.\n*[[Conor Grant]], professional footballer.\n*[[George Green (footballer, born 1996)|George Green]], professional footballer.\n*[[Niall Watson]], professional footballer.\n*[[Tom Scully]], professional footballer.\n*[[Terry McPhillips]], former professional footballer.<ref>[http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/junior-football/2009/12/22/tms-s-dedication-to-youth-football-earns-prestigious-fa-award-100252-25444343/ Liverpool echo]</ref>\n*[[Peter Charles]], [[show jumping|Show jumper]] and [[2012 London Olympics|Olympic]] gold medalist.\n*[[Ninja (video game player)|Ninja]], professional fortnite expert.\n*[[Rick Astley]], global treasure, he will never give you up or let you down!\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sefton.gov.uk/ Sefton Metropolitan Borough Council official site]\n*[http://www.mass.freeuk.com// Associates of the Sisters of Mercy official site]\n*[http://www.mercyworld.org/ Website of the Sisters of Mercy]\n\n{{Schools in Sefton}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in the Archdiocese of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1957]]\n[[Category:1957 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Sisters of Mercy schools]]\n[[Category:Voluntary aided schools in England]]\n[[Category:Maghull]]\n", "name_user": "Vikkstar123456789", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable former pupils)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maricourt_Catholic_School"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Mynarski VC School", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Is a middle school in the Canadian city of Winnipeg, Manitoba.}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                = AMVC / Andrew Mynarski VC School\n| image               = File:Andrew Mynarski VC School and Nugahas Nahte Park.jpg\n| caption             = Andrew Mynarski VC School and Nugahas-Nahte Park\n| address             = 1111 Machray Avenue\n| city                = [[Winnipeg]]\n| province            = [[Manitoba]]\n| postcode            = [[List of R postal codes of Canada|R2X 1H6]]\n| country             = Canada\n| coordinates         = {{coord|49|56|09|N|97|09|51|W|region:CA-MB|display=inline,title}}\n| schooltype          = Public junior high school\n| motto               = Home of the Lancasters\n| district            = [[Winnipeg School Division]]\n| principal           = Cristina Da Mata\n| grades_label        = [[Education in Canada#Levels in education|Grades]]\n| grades              = 7-9\n| students            = 394\n| staff               = 44\n| language            = English\n| colours             = Black and White {{color box|black}}{{color box|white}}\n| homepage            = [https://www.winnipegsd.ca/schools/AndrewMynarski/Pages/default.aspx/ Page]\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Mynarski VC School''' (known more commonly as '''AMVC'''), is a [[middle school]] in the shaughnessy park area of [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]].  The school was built in 1954 and opened officially in September 1955. The school is named after [[Victoria Cross]] recipient [[Andrew Mynarski|Andrew Charles Mynarski.]]\nAMVC's sports teams are named Lancasters.\n\n==History==\n\n===World Harmony Run===\nOn May 11, 2006. The [[Peace Run|WHR]] started its run in Winnipeg. Andrew Mynarski VC School and its feeder schools, [[Lord Nelson School|Lord Nelson]] and [[Robertson School|Robertson]], held a torch relay that began at 9:00 am and ended with the final ceremony at 11:00 am. Andrew Mynarski VC. At the half-way point between the two schools, the torch was relayed from the Lord Nelson runners to the Andrew Mynarski runners led by teacher Coleen Heuchert, and it was off to another ceremony at Andrew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldharmonyrun.org/canada/news/2006/mb/0511.html|title=Canada 11 May: Winnipeg {{!}} World Harmony Run|website=www.worldharmonyrun.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Peace Run|date=2019-09-29|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Peace_Run&oldid=918649374|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.winnipegsd.ca/schools/AndrewMynarski/Pages/default.aspx Andrew Mynarski VC School]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:High schools in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1955]]\n[[Category:1951 establishments in Manitoba]]\n\n\n{{Manitoba-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{COI}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Is a middle school in the Canadian city of Winnipeg, Manitoba.}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                = AMVC / Andrew Mynarski VC School\n| image               = File:Andrew Mynarski VC School and Nugahas Nahte Park.jpg\n| caption             = Andrew Mynarski VC School and Nugahas-Nahte Park\n| address             = 1111 Machray Avenue\n| city                = [[Winnipeg]]\n| province            = [[Manitoba]]\n| postcode            = [[List of R postal codes of Canada|R2X 1H6]]\n| country             = Canada\n| coordinates         = {{coord|49|56|09|N|97|09|51|W|region:CA-MB|display=inline